[6] Cholera - Mozambique (Nampula)
Date: Tue, 21 Mar 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AllAfrica.com and Agencia de Informacao de Mocambique (Maputo)
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200603210545.html>

Last week's outbreak of cholera in the northern Mozambican province of
Nampula, which has so far claimed at least 9 lives, is spreading to other
districts, reports Tuesday's issue of the daily paper "Noticias". The
outbreak was first noted in Monapo and Malema districts, but has now
reached Meconta district, where 30 new cases were recorded in the last 2
days, all admitted to the Namialo health center.
The Namialo administrative post, on the crossroads between the main highway
from Nampula city to the port of Nacala, and the road to the northernmost
province of Cabo Delgado, had been notifying a number of cases of acute
diarrhea in adults over the last few days, and laboratory analysis, carried
out in Nampula city, confirmed that this was indeed cholera. But no deaths
have so far been reported here.
Namialo has been facing a serious water supply crisis, and with the recent
heavy rains people started using water directly from the Monapo river,
drinking it without any treatment. The health authorities believe this is
the source of contamination. To deal with the situation, district and
health authorities in Meconta have launched a joint awareness campaign to
mobilize people to observe prevention measures, namely the use of chlorine
or boiling the water before drinking it.
According to health minister Ivo Garrido, since the start of this year
about 3000 cases of cholera have been notified. The overwhelming majority
-- over 80 percent -- have been in the central province of Sofala. The
other provinces that have notified cases are Manica and Zambezia.
--
